Each firm's cost function is given by \( c_s(y) = \frac{1}{3} y^3 + 2 \). The marginal cost (MC) is derived by taking the derivative of the cost function with respect to \( y \): \[ \text{MC} = \frac{d}{dy} \left( \frac{1}{3} y^3 + 2 \right) = y^2 \] In a competitive market, firms produce where marginal cost equals the market price \( p \): \[ y^2 = p \implies y = \sqrt{p} \] However, we must consider the firm's ability to cover its fixed costs. The fixed cost is 2, so the firm will only produce if the revenue from sales covers this fixed cost. The revenue is \( p \cdot y \). Setting this equal to the fixed cost: \[ p \cdot y = 2 \] Substituting \( y = \sqrt{p} \): \[ p \cdot \sqrt{p} = 2 \implies p^{3/2} = 2 \implies p = 2^{2/3} = \sqrt[3]{4} \] Thus, the firm will produce \( y = \sqrt{p} \) if \( p \geq \sqrt[3]{4} \) and will shut down (produce zero) otherwise. For 100 identical firms, the industry supply function is: \[ Y = 100 \cdot \sqrt{p} \quad \text{for} \quad p \geq \sqrt[3]{4} \] Otherwise, the industry supply is zero. Therefore, the short run industry supply function is: \[ \boxed{Y = \begin{cases} 100 \sqrt{p} & \text{if } p \geq \sqrt[3]{4}, \\ 0 & \text{otherwise}. \end{cases}} \]
